# Droidspaces mandatory kernel options missing from this tree's gki_defconfig.
# The other 33 it requires are already on. Enabled at build time by the workflow,
# never in gki_defconfig, so the four shipping flavors are untouched.
#
# CONFIG_SYSVIPC is the load-bearing one: it needs scripts/droidspaces/integrate.sh
# to have relocated sysvsem/sysvshm into task_struct's KABI reserve first, or every
# prebuilt vendor module reads the wrong offsets and the device bootloops.
#
# Upstream's list calls the conntrack netlink option NF_CONNTRACK_NETLINK. No such
# symbol exists -- the kernel has always called it NF_CT_NETLINK. Copying a
# requirements list without checking each name resolves gets you a build that
# fails at the last step.
#
# CGROUP_DEVICE and CGROUP_PIDS are dropped, and this is the reason the first
# build of this flavor bootlooped on-device. Each adds one entry to
# enum cgroup_subsys_id, which grows CGROUP_SUBSYS_COUNT, which resizes
# struct css_set.subsys[] -- a struct task_struct->cgroups points into. That
# shifts the genksyms CRC of every exported symbol reachable from task_struct,
# which is most of the kernel's vendor-facing surface: __put_task_struct alone
# moved from 0x610b6b8b to 0x53fd3973 with either config on by itself, measured
# by hand-running genksyms against both trees. Every prebuilt vendor module that
# calls anything taking a task_struct* then fails its CRC check and refuses to
# load -- display, touch, camera, UFS. That is the bootloop.
#
# The task_struct relocation in integrate.sh is NOT the cause: with these two
# off, __put_task_struct's CRC is 0x610b6b8b again -- an exact match to the
# boot-tested base -- with SYSVIPC, the relocation, and the other 9 options all
# still on. Verified by hand-building genksyms and diffing the preprocessed
# -D__GENKSYMS__ output between trees, not by inspection.
#
# GKI-Custom (github.com/rvalyi/GKI-Custom) ships the identical relocation AND
# CGROUP_DEVICE=y, and hits this same break -- their fix is a patch forcing
# kernel/module.c's check_version() to always return success, unconditionally.
# Not adopted here: that does not fix the incompatibility, it stops the kernel
# from ever refusing ANY mismatched module, including a real future break.
#
# Device/pid cgroup resource limits are unavailable to containers as a result.
# Namespace isolation (the SYSVIPC/PID_NS/USER_NS work) is unaffected.
#
# CONFIG_USER_NS is a deliberate security tradeoff. Android disables unprivileged
# user namespaces because they are a well-worn local-privilege-escalation surface.
# Containers need them. That cost belongs to this flavor and no other.
SYSVIPC
PID_NS
USER_NS
DEVTMPFS
FW_LOADER_COMPRESS
BRIDGE_NETFILTER
NF_TABLES
NETFILTER_XT_MATCH_ADDRTYPE
NF_CT_NETLINK
